        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity for the CO(9-8) line:
The estimate below assuming that we have 4 hours observation on source.
The resolution at 244.561 GHz (observed frequency of the molecular line CO(9-8)), for 1.5 km baseline is 0.207''.
Noise for 2 h of observation at that frequency, bandwidth per polarization 30 km/s, precipitable water vapour 1.262 mm, is 0.225 mJy for this source. The relative flux ratio of S_{CO(9-8)}/S_{CO(4-3)} of a QSO  vary from  0.6 ~ 1 depending on whether it is in a lower excited state or lies in average QSOs range (see Figure 2 (right)). Namely, the flux S_{CO(9-8)} is about 6 ~ 10 mJy, the Signal-to-Noise (S/N) ratios for A,BC, DEF are 11, 11, 6  and  18, 18, 7 for a lower limit case and an average case respectively.
However, the estimate above does not take into account for the fact that the source is spatially resolved which implies the S/N would reduce. Since the synthesis beam using in Riechers 2011 ~ 8'' and still has not yet resolved the three blobs of images, one may guess the size of total model images (before convolving with the synthesis beam) ~ 1/3 of the beam ~ 2.7''. The A images contributes 27% namely its model size ~ 0.7'' namely ~ 3 beams if the size of the synthesis beam is 0.2''. Assuming a uniform brightness distribution profile of A image the S/N ratio reduces by a factor of 2 due to resolving it. It implies that the S/N ratios of A, BC, DEF images are 9, 9, 4 if B1359+154 is a normal QSO. These ratios reduce to 6, 6, 3 for the lower limit case. 

Sensitivity for a possible detect the water H2O(2-1) line:
As already mention before (material document), we estimate the S/N ~ 2. However, the effect of resolving source is not yet taken into account, namely the S/N should be 1. if we assume the size of continuum emission ~ size of the CO line.

Imaging:
At ~240 GHz, the primary beam of 12 m antenna ~ 25'', the upper limit scale of the source ~ 3'' is well within 1/3 of it.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
